hands_on_practices.problem:
A constant-volume batch reactor of volume $V$ initially contains a pure species $A$ at concentration $C_{A0}$ and undergoes the irreversible reaction $2A \to P$. Let the extent of reaction $\xi(t)$ be defined by the stoichiometric relation $N_i(t) = N_{i0} + \nu_i \,\xi(t)$, where $\nu_i$ is the stoichiometric number of species $i$ (negative for reactants, positive for products), and $N_i$ is the molar amount of species $i$. Define the rate of reaction per unit volume as $r(t) \equiv \dfrac{1}{V}\dfrac{d\xi}{dt}$. The kinetics are described by a generalized power-law $r(t) = k\,C_A(t)^{\,n}$ with $k>0$ and order $n>0$. The initial condition is $C_A(0)=C_{A0}$.

Which option gives a set of relations that are all simultaneously consistent with the stoichiometry, the extent-of-reaction definition, and the kinetic rate law, and that yield the correct integrated rate law for $n \neq 1$ together with the correct half-life $t_{1/2}$, while also handling the special case $n=1$ correctly?

A. 
(i) $C_A(t) = C_{A0} - \dfrac{2\,\xi(t)}{V}$; 
(ii) $-\dfrac{dC_A}{dt} = 2\,r$; 
(iii) For $n \neq 1$: $C_A(t)^{\,1-n} = C_{A0}^{\,1-n} + 2\,(n-1)\,k\,t$ and $t_{1/2} = \dfrac{2^{\,n-1}-1}{2\,(n-1)\,k\,C_{A0}^{\,n-1}}$; for $n=1$: $C_A(t) = C_{A0}\,e^{-2\,k\,t}$ and $t_{1/2} = \dfrac{\ln 2}{2\,k}$.

B.
(i) $C_A(t) = C_{A0} - \dfrac{\xi(t)}{V}$; 
(ii) $-\dfrac{dC_A}{dt} = r$; 
(iii) For $n \neq 1$: $C_A(t)^{\,1-n} = C_{A0}^{\,1-n} + (n-1)\,k\,t$ and $t_{1/2} = \dfrac{2^{\,n-1}-1}{(n-1)\,k\,C_{A0}^{\,n-1}}$; for $n=1$: $C_A(t) = C_{A0}\,e^{-k\,t}$ and $t_{1/2} = \dfrac{\ln 2}{k}$.

C.
(i) $C_A(t) = C_{A0} - \dfrac{2\,\xi(t)}{V}$; 
(ii) $-\dfrac{dC_A}{dt} = r$; 
(iii) For $n \neq 1$: $C_A(t)^{\,1-n} = C_{A0}^{\,1-n} + (n-1)\,k\,t$ and $t_{1/2} = \dfrac{2^{\,n-1}-1}{(n-1)\,k\,C_{A0}^{\,n-1}}$; for $n=1$: $C_A(t) = C_{A0}\,e^{-k\,t}$ and $t_{1/2} = \dfrac{\ln 2}{k}$.

D.
(i) $C_A(t) = C_{A0} + \dfrac{2\,\xi(t)}{V}$; 
(ii) $-\dfrac{dC_A}{dt} = 2\,r$; 
(iii) For $n \neq 1$: $C_A(t)^{\,1-n} = C_{A0}^{\,1-n} + 2\,(n-1)\,k\,t$ and $t_{1/2} = \dfrac{2^{\,n-1}-1}{2\,(n-1)\,k\,C_{A0}^{\,n-1}}$; for $n=1$: $C_A(t) = C_{A0}\,e^{-k\,t}$ and $t_{1/2} = \dfrac{\ln 2}{k}$.
